Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of @oil{} onto a #baking tray{} and pop in your oven. Bring a #large saucepan{} of water to the boil on high heat with a pinch of @salt{}. Peel the @potatoes{900%g}, chop them into 4cm chunks. Trim the @courgette{1} and slice into 1cm thick rounds. Pick the @mint{1/2} leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife.

Peel the @garlic clove{1} and quarter lengthways. Take your @lamb roasting joint{450%g} and use a #small knife{} to poke small holes about 2cm deep. TIP: 1 hole per quarter of garlic. Push a piece of garlic into each hole. Keep to one side, we will roast the lamb later.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the #pot{} and sprinkle on half the @plain flour{3%tbsp}. Give your pot a shake to fluff up the potato.

Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Sprinkle over a pinch of @salt{}. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven for ~{45-50%minutes}, turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, heat a #frying pan{} over high heat (no oil). When hot, add the courgettes and cook until charred, ~{3%minutes} one each. Keep to one side we, will re-heat before serving. Wipe the pan clean.

Season the lamb with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{} and a drizzle of @oil{}. Transfer to another baking tray and roast in the oven for ~{30-40%minutes} (depending on size) for medium rare. Add an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your lamb more cooked. Rest wrapped loosely in #foil{} for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing.

> IMPORTANT: The lamb is safe to eat when the outside is cooked.

Meanwhile, heat a glug of @oil for the sauce{} in a #saucepan{} over medium heat, stir in the remaining flour and cook for ~{1%minute}. Gradually stir in the @water for the gravy{4%tbsp}, bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that may form. Stir in and dissolve the @red wine jus paste{2%tbsp}, then lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}. Season to taste with @salt and @ground black pepper{}.

In a #small bowl{}, mix the mint with the @balsamic vinegar{2%tbsp} and oil and set aside.

While the lamb rests, pop the @Tenderstem® broccoli{150%g} and @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} on the baking tray you used for the lamb, drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt and @ground black pepper{}. Roast until tender and the tomatoes have popped, ~{10%minutes}. Add the charred courgette slices to the tray for the last ~{5%minutes} to warm through.

Remove the netting from the lamb, slice thinly and arrange on your plates. Pop the roasties and Provencal veggies alongside. Reheat the gravy if necessary, spoon all over and finish with a drizzle of the minty dressing!